05377nam a22008535i 9780812297768DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808122977687 a10.9783/97808122977682doi  a(DE-B1597)573147  a(OCoLC)1250089514  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a954/.12231 aSur, Malini, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aJungle Passports :bFences, Mobility, and Citizenship at the Northeast India-Bangladesh Border /cMalini Sur. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (248 p.) :b23 illus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Ethnography of Political Violence00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tTimeline -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The Rowmari-Tura Road -- tChapter 2. Rice Wars and Nation Building -- tChapter 3. Cow Smuggling and Fang-Fung -- tChapter 4. Kinship, Identities, and “Jungle Passports” -- tChapter 5. Fear, Reverence, and the Fence -- tChapter 6. Bangladeshi “Suspects” and Indian “Citizens” in Assam -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the nineteenth century, a succession of states has classified the inhabitants of what are now the borderlands of Northeast India and Bangladesh as Muslim "frontier peasants," "savage mountaineers," and Christian "ethnic minorities," suspecting them to be disloyal subjects, spies, and traitors. In Jungle Passports Malini Sur follows the struggles of these people to secure shifting land, gain access to rice harvests, and smuggle the cattle and garments upon which their livelihoods depend against a background of violence, scarcity, and India's construction of one of the world's longest and most highly militarized border fences.Jungle Passports recasts established notions of citizenship and mobility along violent borders. Sur shows how the division of sovereignties and distinct regimes of mobility and citizenship push undocumented people to undertake perilous journeys across previously unrecognized borders every day. Paying close attention to the forces that shape the life-worlds of deportees, refugees, farmers, smugglers, migrants, bureaucrats, lawyers, clergy, and border troops, she reveals how reciprocity and kinship and the enforcement of state violence, illegality, and border infrastructures shape the margins of life and death. Combining years of ethnographic and archival fieldwork, her thoughtful and evocative book is a poignant testament to the force of life in our era of closed borders, insularity, and "illegal migration."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectszBangladesh. 0aBorder securityxSocial aspectszIndia, Northeastern. 0aBorderlandszBangladesh. 0aBorderlandszIndia, Northeastern. 0aBoundariesxAnthropological aspects. 0aCitizenshipzBangladesh. 0aCitizenshipzIndia. 0aTransnationalism. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aAsian Studies.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021 Englishz978311075400108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2021z9783110753776oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021 Englishz978311075418608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology 2021z9783110753967oZDB-23-DSW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073921340uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081229776840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/97808